\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
When the system changes from 
\series bold
Condition A
\series default
 to 
\series bold
Condition B
\series default
, does the partition function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 increase, decrease, or stay the same? If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{Z}$
\end_inset

 changes, by what factor does it change? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When the system changes from 
\series bold
Condition A
\series default
 to 
\series bold
Condition B
\series default
, does the probability of finding the system in state 2 increase, decrease,
 or stay the same? If the probability changes, by what factor does it change?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When the system changes from 
\series bold
Condition A
\series default
 to 
\series bold
Condition B
\series default
, does the ratio of the probability of finding the system in state 1 to
 the probability of finding the system in state 2, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(1)/P(2)$
\end_inset

, increase, decrease, or stay the same? If the probability ratio changes,
 by what factor does it change? 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution*
Because the system is in contact with a heat reservoir and there is no particle
 exchange, we're thinking in a canonical ensemble, and we know that in this
 ensemble, the partition function is defined as the sum over states of the
 Boltzmann factors, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{Z}=\sum_{i}\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/k_{B}T$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{i}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to the energy of that state.
 Now, with this in mind we can write down the partition function for the
 system in the Condition A, and Condition B, and then compare them.
 Let's do that, for A, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{Z}_{A} & =\sum_{i}\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{i}\right),\\
 & =\exp\left(-\beta\epsilon_{0}\right)+\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{1}\right)+\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{2}\right)+\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{3}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}=0,\varepsilon_{1}=1,\varepsilon_{2}=2,\varepsilon_{3}=3$
\end_inset

, we can write the previous expression in a nicer way, of course, but for
 our purposes that will be enough.
 Now, let's write the partition function for the B condition, this is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{Z}_{B}=\sum_{i}\exp\left(-\beta\epsilon_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon_{i}=\varepsilon+\Delta E$
\end_inset

, then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathcal{Z}_{B} & =\sum_{i}\exp\left(-\beta\left(\varepsilon_{i}+\Delta E\right)\right),\\
 & =\sum_{i}\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{i}\right)\exp\left(-\beta\Delta E\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and in the last expression, the term with the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E$
\end_inset

 is independent of the sum, then we can put that term outside the sum symbol,
 thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{Z}_{B}=\exp\left(-\beta\Delta E\right)\sum_{i}\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{i}\right),
\]

\end_inset

but the expression in the sum is the partition function for the Condition
 A, this is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{Z}_{B}=\exp\left(-\beta\Delta E\right)\mathcal{Z}_{A},
\]

\end_inset

then, as we can see, the partition function increases by a factor of determined
 by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

excess
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of energy in the new configuration, this is 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp\left(-\beta\Delta E\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let's calculate the probability for finding the system in the state
 2, in the Condition A, this is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(\varepsilon_{2}\right)_{A}=\frac{\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{2}\right)}{\mathcal{Z}_{A}},
\]

\end_inset

now, let's compute the same probability using Condition B, this is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P\left(\epsilon_{2}\right)_{B} & =\frac{\exp\left(-\beta\epsilon_{2}\right)}{\mathcal{Z}_{B}},\\
 & =\frac{\exp\left(-\beta\left(\varepsilon_{2}+\Delta E\right)\right)}{\exp\left(-\beta\Delta E\right)\mathcal{Z}_{A}},\\
 & =\frac{\exp\left(-\beta\Delta E\right)\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{2}\right)}{\exp\left(-\beta\Delta E\right)\mathcal{Z}_{A}},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and as we can see the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

excess
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the partition function cancels out, leaving us with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(\epsilon_{2}\right)_{B}=\frac{\exp\left(-\beta\varepsilon_{2}\right)}{\mathcal{Z}_{A}},
\]

\end_inset

but this is the same expression for the probability in the Condition A,
 therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(\epsilon_{2}\right)_{B}=P\left(\varepsilon_{2}\right)_{A},
\]

\end_inset

and from this we can conclude that the probability stays the same.
\end_layout

